Xbox=E2=80=99s Announcement
-------------------

The Verge ( https://www.theverge.com/2024/2/16/24074729/microsoft-phil-spen=
cer-xbox-everywhere-memo ) obtained a memo that Microsoft Gaming CEO Phil S=
pencer sent to his employees:

When we look at the state of our medium, we see players increasingly gaming=
 on multiple devices, but their experience is defined by the fragmentation =
created by platform silos. Multi-device players have to navigate multiple i=
dentities, entitlement libraries, communities, wallets, and reward programs=
. Similarly, the industry=E2=80=99s biggest franchises increasingly ship ac=
ross multiple devices, requiring creators to build and manage multiple inst=
ances of their games, leading to higher costs and fragmented communities. A=
ll of this friction creates a tremendous opportunity for us to meet the nee=
ds of multi-device players and creators.

We have a different vision for the future of gaming. A future where players=
 have a unified experience across devices. A future where players can easil=
y discover a vast array of games with a diverse spectrum of business models=
. A future where more creators are empowered to realize their creative visi=
on, reach a global audience, unite their communities, and succeed commercia=
lly. A future where every screen is an Xbox.

This is a future where Xbox is everywhere=E2=80=94consistent with our promi=
se to empower players to =E2=80=9Cplay the games you want, with the people =
you want, anywhere you want.=E2=80=9D

The details of what this entails are still sparse; for now 4 unspecified Xb=
ox-exclusive games are headed for the PS5 and Switch, and, well, that=E2=80=
=99s it. In fact, Spencer said in the podcast announcing the change ( https=
://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3DKGlD9SO3rKU ) that it was =E2=80=9Cnot a chang=
e to our fundamental exclusive strategy.=E2=80=9D Spencer explained how the=
y chose the games in question:

We looked at games that are over a year old, so they=E2=80=99ve been on Xbo=
x and PC for a while. A couple of the games are community-driven games, new=
 games, kind of first iterations of a franchise, that have reached their fu=
ll potential on Xbox and PC. There=E2=80=99s always growth, franchises that=
 we obviously want to continue to invest in. Part of having the ability to =
continue to invest is that the businesses behind those franchises continue.=
 We thinks it=E2=80=99s important that these services-based games that have=
 communities behind them, that they can have confidence that they=E2=80=99r=
e going to exist in the future. So two of them, kind of community-driven ga=
mes that will end up on other platforms and will give us the ability to con=
tinue to invest in them. We think that=E2=80=99s great for the business and=
 great for the communities. More players to play with.

Two of the other games are smaller games that were never really meant to be=
 built as kind of platform exclusives and all the fanfare that goes around =
that, but games that our teams really wanted to go build that we love suppo=
rting creative endeavors across our studios regardless of size. And as they=
=E2=80=99ve realized their full potential on Xbox and PC, we see an opportu=
nity to utilize the other platforms as a place to just drive more business =
value out of those games, allowing us to invest in maybe future iterations =
of those, so sequels to those, or just other games like that in our portfol=
io. And when we don=E2=80=99t damage Xbox and we can grow our business usin=
g what other platforms have to help us with that, we=E2=80=99re going to do=
 that. And that=E2=80=99s really the story behind these four games.

And last thing I=E2=80=99ll say looking forward, I think there is an intere=
sting story for us of introducing Xbox franchises to players on other platf=
orms to get them more interested in Xbox. We think there=E2=80=99s a good b=
rand value for Xbox there. So four games, no promise beyond that. So if you=
=E2=80=99re on those other platforms and you see these four games coming, p=
lease don=E2=80=99t take it as some signal that everything=E2=80=99s coming=
. It=E2=80=99s not. And we=E2=80=99re going to learn.

That =E2=80=94 in contrast to the memo =E2=80=94 actually doesn=E2=80=99t s=
ound like much of a change at all. Maybe I was premature! Still, note this =
answer from an interview Spencer did with Tom Warren of The Verge ( https:/=
/www.theverge.com/24073666/microsoft-gaming-phil-spencer-interview-ps5-swit=
ch-games ) ; Warren asked Spencer =E2=80=9CWhat is Xbox to Microsoft now?=
=E2=80=9D:

Xbox is our gaming platform and content business. It=E2=80=99s the number o=
ne consumer business that Microsoft has. I think you might have commented o=
n looking at last quarter=E2=80=99s earnings, we=E2=80=99re now with the th=
ird largest [business] in the company. It=E2=80=99s an important business, =
it=E2=80=99s a consumer category that is driven by technology and creativit=
y. It=E2=80=99s a partner-lead business for us, so we get a lot of feedback=
 and interaction with some of the world=E2=80=99s best creators. It=E2=80=
=99s been amazing the support that this company has given this business ove=
r the last five or six years. Honestly, it sounds so cheesy for me to say i=
t, but I=E2=80=99ve never been as excited as I am now about the opportunity=
 ahead for us.

Spencer did not call it a console, even though the podcast promised new har=
dware, both this Christmas and for the next generation. What the podcast di=
d say is that Game Pass will only be on Xbox (and reiterated that all Micro=
soft games, including Activision games, will be on Game Pass).

Microsoft=E2=80=99s Messy Middle
------------------------

So, what to make of all of this?

First, from my perspective as an analyst, it=E2=80=99s always important to =
not only be wary of confirmation bias, but to also remember that these are =
real businesses I=E2=80=99m writing about, that have to maintain revenue an=
d communities while making changes. That, though, only clouds the picture: =
is Spencer simply slow-rolling a much larger change by insisting that nothi=
ng is different for now =E2=80=94=C2=A0the =E2=80=9Cplease don=E2=80=99t st=
op buying Xbox=E2=80=99s yet=E2=80=9D approach?

This is possible, but I think I=E2=80=99m going to go the other way: my rea=
ction is that actually this really isn=E2=80=99t a huge change, and very we=
ll might not lead to a bigger one in the foreseeable future. The big tell i=
s the insistence that Xbox Game Pass will remain exclusive to Xbox: the fun=
damental distinction is whether a service differentiates the hardware, or i=
f the hardware differentiates the service, or exists to benefit the service=
 in some way. To take the smartphone analogy, Android exists to ensure acce=
ss to Google services; Google, though, rightly puts its services on iOS; er=
go, Google is pursuing a services strategy, not a hardware one (of course i=
t can, and has in the past, gotten complicated). In this case declaring tha=
t Xbox Game Pass will be exclusive to Xbox strongly suggests that Xbox cont=
inues to be a hardware-defined business at the core.

Now the specifics are not so clean cut: the reason to keep the Xbox hardwar=
e platform is less about hardware margin (which is often negative, particul=
arly at initial launch), but rather to earn licensing fees and store revenu=
e. It seems likely to me that that is still an important part of penciling =
out Xbox Game Pass=E2=80=99s long-term profitability (because putting games=
 on Game Pass does diminish revenue from gamers who might have bought multi=
ple games that they now get as part of their subscription). That sacrifice =
is paid for by more people buying Xbox=E2=80=99s so that they can get Xbox =
Game Pass. Indeed, it seems obvious enough that I probably should have bett=
er forecast what Spencer and team actually announced.

At the same time, Microsoft is still a huge game publisher, and the best wa=
y to make money on the fixed cost of developing a game (or the ongoing cost=
 of running a community-based game) is to have said game on as many platfor=
ms as possible; that means PS5 and Switch for a non-trivial number of games=
 in the portfolio, particularly if those games are not likely compelling en=
ough to drive switchers.

And so, in the end, Xbox ended up in the messy middle: Xbox Game Pass doesn=
=E2=80=99t make complete financial sense unless its driving a broader busin=
ess, so Xbox hardware will remain a thing, but a massive game publishing bu=
siness doesn=E2=80=99t make complete financial sense if you=E2=80=99re not =
getting full leverage on your costs. And so Microsoft is going to try and h=
ave it both ways, in large part because they have two big economic drivers =
running in opposite directions.

Apple in Europe, Continued
--------------------------

This, I think it=E2=80=99s safe to say, is not a subject that is going anyw=
here. Some notes on three recent news stories:

*Progressive Web Apps:* Apple is disabling progressive web apps (PWAs) in t=
he E.U. ( https://www.theverge.com/2024/2/15/24074182/apple-drops-support-i=
phone-web-apps-eu-dma ) PWAs are web apps you can save to your home screen;=
 they run in their own container and, as of only a year ago, have access to=
 things like notifications. They are, in theory, an alternative to apps in =
the App Store, but in reality, developers have complained about Apple=E2=80=
=99s implementation and the lack of platform features like the aforemention=
ed notifications.

The DMA, meanwhile, requires Apple to treat all browsers equally, and let a=
ny browser be the default. This, presumably, means letting any browser crea=
te a PWA. Apple has decided they don=E2=80=99t want to do the work to make =
this happen, so instead, in the E.U., there just won=E2=80=99t be any PWAs =
at all; you can still save a shortcut to your home screen, but it will just=
 open in your default browser, whichever one it is.

This is, obviously, really annoying, but also abides by the regulation: the=
 DMA doesn=E2=80=99t say that an iPhone has to have PWAs. And, it must be n=
oted, this aligns with Apple=E2=80=99s incentives: if you want something li=
ke notifications you will have to make an app and put it in the App Store. =
In short, everyone is being treated equally, which the DMA requires; it jus=
t turns out that (as is so often the case) equally means equally bad.

*Apple to be Fined in Spotify Case:* The Financial Times ( https://www.ft.c=
om/content/1e677a7e-9494-4f5b-a724-9e58ef26b34f ) is reporting that Apple w=
ill be fined =E2=82=AC500 million for not allowing Spotify to link out to i=
ts website. This is not, broadly speaking, about Apple=E2=80=99s anti-steer=
ing rules as a whole; rather, it=E2=80=99s a more basic unfair competition =
case rooted in the fact that Apple Music is competitive with Spotify, and i=
s being favored by Apple=E2=80=99s platform decisions.

I think, as I noted a year ago ( https://stratechery.com/2023/eu-narrows-ap=
ple-case-snaps-my-ai/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZW=
NoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5w=
YXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InV=
yaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDIzL2V1LW5hcnJvd3MtYXBwbGUtY2FzZS=
1zbmFwcy1teS1haS8iXX0sImV4cCI6MTcxMDk0MjM0MSwiaWF0IjoxNzA4MzUwMzQxLCJpc3MiO=
iJodHRwczovL2FwaS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUvb2F1dGgiLCJzY29wZSI6ImZlZWQ6cmVhZCBh=
cnRpY2xlOnJlYWQgYXNzZXQ6cmVhZCBjYXRlZ29yeTpyZWFkIGVudGl0bGVtZW50cyIsInN1YiI=
6IlJzZXVZRThqZ0hlUHBXSmYxZkFiNEMiLCJ1c2UiOiJhY2Nlc3MifQ.ae1IJMgz1DImN7B5Lqi=
N0WsIOKF99E4bHwmZvsuEXdBO8Nac96M0v_A0J5chhAte5r0PFYAB-Chxui2ohKiLbUVcPZL36x=
F3o5bMqj7j-TxvcanE_sCs6DeCofnQxKCHHs50DbxIZjv2Gw-P50wsZtP1oGVYxnE_2W6xtrLGJ=
yf6avo29VyJ3o0tqnNrCHwdnrCx5LmbMqGCIEyXS5d6riKxSrqxoAMa8EkRBvoe6t3ohhPKtO9L=
pRCcVkiUhAWVJiJOjhEmtC5fTejL435LsHtzBB8ymYYImAYKhsmRqYxNIeLu0b6w1dW37R2mNzQ=
g-PiyLu28o2kn1_oJzmMJbg ) , this is an obviously correct decision. Apple=E2=
=80=99s favoring of its services like Apple Music, iBooks, and the iTunes S=
tore relative to their direct competitors is flagrantly anticompetitive: al=
ternative services have to either have a customer-hostile user experience (=
by not actually being able to tell them how to buy or subscribe) or they ha=
ve to compete at a 30% cost disadvantage (which goes directly to their comp=
etitor). It=E2=80=99s completely unfair.

The European Commission hasn=E2=80=99t yet issued a press release or statem=
ent of facts (but the Financial Times is always the outlet where these deci=
sions are leaked, so I=E2=80=99m sure they=E2=80=99re coming soon), so the =
question of remedies remains unclear (and, to be fair, will probably be unc=
lear regardless). What seems clear to me is that while there is a valid deb=
ate to be had about apps generally, services that directly compete with App=
le services should have the unencumbered right to link out to the web, no s=
pecial entitlements or payment to Apple required. Apple might think it is e=
ntitled to app revenue derived on the phone, but even if you accept that pr=
emise, they shouldn=E2=80=99t be able to leverage that to build directly co=
mpeting services.

*Epic Launching iOS App Store in EU:* Apple has, to its credit (as Epic CEO=
 Tim Sweeney acknowledged ( https://twitter.com/timsweeneyepic/status/17585=
33135774495033 ) ), reinstated Epic=E2=80=99s developer account in Europe s=
o that the company can launch an alternative App Store under Apple=E2=80=99=
s new EU rules ( https://stratechery.com/2024/apple-and-the-dmc-apple-and-o=
r-a-reluctant-apple-apologist/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6I=
